A rotation by \( k \) degrees is equivalent to multiplication by \( e^{i k^\circ} \), and a reflection across the \( y \)-axis is equivalent to multiplying by \( -1 \) and taking the complex conjugate. Thus, the transformation \( T_k \) can be written as: \[ T_k(z) = -e^{-i k^\circ} \overline{z} \] Applying these transformations sequentially, we track the effect on the complex number \( z \). Starting with \( z_0 = 1 \) (the point \( (1,0) \)): - \( z_1 = T_1(z_0) = -e^{-i 1^\circ} \) - \( z_2 = T_2(z_1) = e^{-i 1^\circ} \) - \( z_3 = T_3(z_2) = -e^{-i 2^\circ} \) - \( z_4 = T_4(z_3) = e^{-i 2^\circ} \) - And so on. We observe a pattern where for even \( n = 2m \), \( z_n = e^{-i m^\circ} \), and for odd \( n = 2m + 1 \), \( z_n = -e^{-i (m + 1)^\circ} \). To return to \( z_n = 1 \): - For even \( n \), \( e^{-i m^\circ} = 1 \) implies \( m \) must be a multiple of 360. The smallest even \( n \) is 720. - For odd \( n \), \( -e^{-i (m + 1)^\circ} = 1 \) implies \( (m + 1) = 180 \). The smallest odd \( n \) is \( 2 \times 179 + 1 = 359 \). Thus, the least positive integer \( n \) is \(\boxed{359}\).
